title: For Sale:  Colt R6830 Lightweight 7.62x39 Like NEW
postcontent:
BUY IT NOW AM GIVEN IT OUT THIS PRICE BECAUSE OF FINANCIAL PROBLEM
This is a RARE opportunity to own a special Colt AR. Under present circumstances perhaps an even better time to act.

Not only is this Colt a rarity in its caliber - 7.62x39, it is in near new condition, but without box, manual, or goodie bag. The firearm has been well kept and was purchased "like new" as a bare gun in the early 90s by the owner I bought it from. A replacement trigger group had been installed and the original was since lost.

This very meticulous 2nd owner removed the Colt carry handle upper, put it away, and replaced it with a flat top (PWS?), put in an accuwedge, changed out the flash suppressor and fired a few rounds now and then with it. He also told me up front his flat top upper would not chamber steel case or poly coated cartridges. Brass was all he ever shot through it. When I purchased it he replaced the upper with the original, still unfired. I have the original flash, and "good guy" 5 round factory steel mag.

SInce I bought it I have exactly 40 rounds through it - also brass FMJ. 20 PMC Bronze and 20 Fiocchi. I can say that the weapon is an absolute joy to fire. The well-balanced old school Sporter design with A2 stock and carry handle, combined with the R6830 buffer spring setup make the felt recoil about a wash compared to a 5.56. (My Colt 6720 M4 shooting 62gr XM855 kicks much harder.) On its iron sights at the back of my 25 yard range this Colt is also accurate - on its first box of ammo from the beanbag it shot sub-2" groups with the PMC.

Included in the sale are some very rare accessories. In addition to the beautiful rifle I am including 4 high capacity magazines: two 20 rd, one 30 round, and the 75 rd drum. No markings but I believe these to be early USA "frankenmags". (This refers to "obvious" grafting the AR15 upper mag body to the AK47 lower.) I have not tested these for cycling but they are in very good to excellent condition. A magazine selection like this is VERY hard to find.

Along with the rifle and mags is a VINTAGE beauty of a scope - 3x20 Colt 1960s Japan manufacture and in near mint condition. Worth $4-500 alone, it is a nice companion piece to the rifle.



Shipping + insurance $30 to your FFL. 

Thank you for looking. Ad reply/PM interest.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 12 Riot Gun: Attn. Cowboy Action Shooters
postcontent:
Pre-64 Model 12 in 12 gauge, with nickel steel barrel and 2.75" chamber. Was a field grade 28" mod choke until I had the barrel professionally shortened and crowned and the bead reset for a current riot-gun configuration.

The gun is a 1954 issue, in excellent mechanical shape and very good cosmetic shape (only flaw is a small area of shallow pitting and bluing loss on left side of receiver). Straight-grain black walnut stocks retain about 85% finish and are crack-free. Bluing and overall fit and finish are excellent. Cylinder-bored 20-inch barrel with a bead sight; chamber and bore are both mirror-bright, as both have just been professionally honed and the barrel back-bored.

Would make an excellent Cowboy Action or Bowling Pin shotgun or deer gun with slugs or buckshot in brush or tight cover. And, of course, it would make a very persuasive and effective home defense gun. This was one of the very few pumpguns (with the Win. Model 97 and early Ithaca 37) ever built without a trigger disconnect, so it can be slam-fired--almost as fast as an autoloader. Compact, well-balanced, and shucks lightning-fast. 

And, of course, it has that unmistakable heft and feel of a pre-64 Winchester, when polished blued steel and real walnut were standard equipment. Unlike today's cheap pumpguns, the only plastic part associated with this gun is the Winchester embossed buttplate. 

I have additional photos that I will gladly email upon request.

 Serious inquiries only, please; do not reply if you are unable or unwilling to pass NICS. 

Respond to this post with a phone number and the best time to call.

title: For Sale:  Patriot's Day-Project Appleseed-Marksmanship Instruction & History & Heritate
location: Throughout the United States, Indiana, United States
postcontent:
Come out and celebrate Patriot's Day with the Revolutionary War Veteran's Association Patriot's Day and attend a Project Appleseed event. Project Appleseed is a 2 day event providing rifle marksmanship instruction and the history and heritage of the Battle of Lexington and Concord which is described as the "Shot heard round the world". For details and locations visit www.appleseedinfo.org

History and Heritage

Project Appleseed is an activity of The Revolutionary War Veterans Association, a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization, dedicated to teaching every American our shared heritage and history as well as traditional rifle marksmanship skills.  Our volunteer instructors travel across the country teaching those who attend about the difficult choices, the heroic actions, and the sacrifices that the Founders made on behalf of modern Americans, all of whom are their posterity.
Our heritage program vividly portrays the Battles of Lexington and Concord with the kind of care and immediacy that is absent from most formal schooling. Modern listeners are confronted with the danger, the fear, and the heartbreaking separations that arose out of the choices made on April 19th, 1775. They are also reminded of the marksmanship skills and masterful organization that ultimately helped set the colonists on the path to success. Those who attend gain a better understanding of the fundamental choices faced by our ancestors as they began to set the stage for the nation we now enjoy.

Marksmanship Clinic 

Our rifle marksmanship program complements our history and heritage.  We teach the traditional American marksmanship skills.  There are, however, several aspects of our marksmanship program that deserve special mention. We are particularly proud of our younger attendees. In accordance with applicable local laws, young people with sufficient maturity are welcome to the Appleseed line and can, with parental permission, join the cadre.  The RWVA recognizes the importance of introducing a wide cross section of Americans to their marksmanship heritage. To encourage participation, we offer our program of instruction at a greatly reduced price to both women, and responsible persons under 21; Finally, an important aspect of our marksmanship program is called “Adaptive Appleseed.” Project Appleseed is serious about bringing our heritage and marksmanship instruction to everyone so we’ve committed ourselves to adapting Appleseed to the special needs of those who have certain physical challenges.
Why teach marksmanship?  Because good shooting requires learning positive traits such as patience, determination, focus, attention to detail, and persistence.   Since these skills are likewise key elements of mature participation in civic activities, we urge our students to take what they have learned about themselves as marksmen and apply it to their participation in their communities and in the wider American society in accordance with their own choices about how Americans should govern themselves. 

Civic Involvement

There are those who feel that America’s future is grim, that is, that America has lost something special and it can never be regained.   And in their consternation they mutter about “dark choices” and the like.  Appleseed has a message for them.   Just over two hundred years ago our ancestors genuinely faced a tough choice.  They could submit to those they felt were depriving them of their rights as Englishmen or they could fight.  Because they chose as they did, we may never have to face their dilemma because we have a third alternative.
So what must you do with your third choice?  Well, you must roll out of the recliner, cut off the computer, turn down the TV and get involved.  That’s it.  Talk to family, talk to friends, interact with neighbors, take part in local community decisions, and become active in whatever political party best fits your idea of how America should be governed.  Write to your elected representative, attend town halls, correspond with newspaper editors, and wholeheartedly enter the discussion in both online and traditional forums.
Read!  Think!  Debate!  Vote!  And finally, we'd really like your help in shaping America's bright future by participating in this program as a student, as an instructor, or as a volunteer in other support roles.  But even if you never pick up a rifle again, know that you are everything that Project Appleseed works for.  You are an involved, committed American making responsible use of the liberties gifted to us so long ago.  The future is what we make -- YOU make -- of it.

title: For Sale:  Patriot's Day-Project Appleseed-Marksmanship Instruction & History & Heritage
location: Throughout the United States, Michigan, United States
postcontent:
Come out and celebrate Patriot's Day with the Revolutionary War Veteran's Association Patriot's Day and attend a Project Appleseed event. Project Appleseed is a 2 day event providing rifle marksmanship instruction and the history and heritage of the Battle of Lexington and Concord which is described as the "Shot heard round the world". For details and locations visit www.appleseedinfo.org

History and Heritage

Project Appleseed is an activity of The Revolutionary War Veterans Association, a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization, dedicated to teaching every American our shared heritage and history as well as traditional rifle marksmanship skills. Our volunteer instructors travel across the country teaching those who attend about the difficult choices, the heroic actions, and the sacrifices that the Founders made on behalf of modern Americans, all of whom are their posterity.
Our heritage program vividly portrays the Battles of Lexington and Concord with the kind of care and immediacy that is absent from most formal schooling. Modern listeners are confronted with the danger, the fear, and the heartbreaking separations that arose out of the choices made on April 19th, 1775. They are also reminded of the marksmanship skills and masterful organization that ultimately helped set the colonists on the path to success. Those who attend gain a better understanding of the fundamental choices faced by our ancestors as they began to set the stage for the nation we now enjoy.

Marksmanship Clinic

Our rifle marksmanship program complements our history and heritage. We teach the traditional American marksmanship skills. There are, however, several aspects of our marksmanship program that deserve special mention. We are particularly proud of our younger attendees. In accordance with applicable local laws, young people with sufficient maturity are welcome to the Appleseed line and can, with parental permission, join the cadre. The RWVA recognizes the importance of introducing a wide cross section of Americans to their marksmanship heritage. To encourage participation, we offer our program of instruction at a greatly reduced price to both women, and responsible persons under 21; Finally, an important aspect of our marksmanship program is called “Adaptive Appleseed.” Project Appleseed is serious about bringing our heritage and marksmanship instruction to everyone so we’ve committed ourselves to adapting Appleseed to the special needs of those who have certain physical challenges.
Why teach marksmanship? Because good shooting requires learning positive traits such as patience, determination, focus, attention to detail, and persistence. Since these skills are likewise key elements of mature participation in civic activities, we urge our students to take what they have learned about themselves as marksmen and apply it to their participation in their communities and in the wider American society in accordance with their own choices about how Americans should govern themselves.

Civic Involvement

There are those who feel that America’s future is grim, that is, that America has lost something special and it can never be regained. And in their consternation they mutter about “dark choices” and the like. Appleseed has a message for them. Just over two hundred years ago our ancestors genuinely faced a tough choice. They could submit to those they felt were depriving them of their rights as Englishmen or they could fight. Because they chose as they did, we may never have to face their dilemma because we have a third alternative.
So what must you do with your third choice? Well, you must roll out of the recliner, cut off the computer, turn down the TV and get involved. That’s it. Talk to family, talk to friends, interact with neighbors, take part in local community decisions, and become active in whatever political party best fits your idea of how America should be governed. Write to your elected representative, attend town halls, correspond with newspaper editors, and wholeheartedly enter the discussion in both online and traditional forums.
Read! Think! Debate! Vote! And finally, we'd really like your help in shaping America's bright future by participating in this program as a student, as an instructor, or as a volunteer in other support roles. But even if you never pick up a rifle again, know that you are everything that Project Appleseed works for. You are an involved, committed American making responsible use of the liberties gifted to us so long ago. The future is what we make -- YOU make -- of it.
